Precondition

1. Learning


GameStop is a classic brick and mortar style store that specializes in the retail sale of hardcopy video games and gaming equpment. It is without a doubt that online retail entities have secured a large amoutn of market capital from GameStop over the last few years. This decline was matched by large investment firms who bet a generous amount of money that the companies stock would continue its downward trend. They made these bets in the form of shorts, or rather, they sold shares with a promise that they would have to buy them back later in the future. If GME fell in price, they would have a lucrative profit. However, if GME failed to fall, short-sellers would have to buy back their shares at the current price (causing a price surge). A few individuals apart of the r/wallstreetbets reddit community realized the opportunity, brought the entire reddit community together, and collectively bought and held many GME shares in order to keep the price high as hedge funds were forced to buy back shorted shares at the current, inflated price. This caused massive surges in the stock price. The little guy profited, the hedge funds lost it all, and the SEC and exchanges have proven to be one of the most curropt entities in history.
Problem: Has the Internet, Specifically the r/wallstreetbets Reddit Forum, Played a Big Role in the 'Meme' Stock Price GME Fiassco?

2. Winnowing


In order to explore our problem, I have chosen two datasets to analyze.

1. GME Closing Price Data from the NYSE
Source: Yahoo Finance https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/GME/history/
This is data reflects the closing price of the GME stock on the NYSE. It is completely unbiased and purlely represents the historical price action of the stock. This data will be useful to track the value of the GME stock over time and be able to compare it to external factors that may have caused its volatility.

2. "wallstreetbets" Google Search Popularity
Source: Google Trends https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?date=today%203-m&q=wall%20street%20bets
This data reflects the frequency that the term "wallstreetbets" was searched on the Google Search Engine. It is also unbiased because if represents historical frequency data. Google Trends has ranked the search frequency with a rating between 0-100 (Less frequent - More frequent). This data will be useful in comparing to GME's historical stock price action. We will be able to see if trends align or not to find out if there is a a correlation between the google search frequency of thge term "wallstreetbets" and the price of the GME stock.

How: We will plot both data sets using consistent x axis in the form of dates over a certain range in time. We will use a line graph to connect datapoints to create a visually appealing representation of the trend of the data.

4. Design



5. Implement



This implementation consists of overlayed lineplots sharing an x axis with independent y axis. The visualization allows us to track changes in each dataset over the same period of time. If changes occur in both sets around the same time, we may be able to draw correlation between the two sets.

6. Deploy



In [65]:
base2 = alt.Chart(df_merge).encode(alt.X('Date', axis=alt.Axis(title='Date'))).properties(title = 'GME Closing Price (Red) VS Wall Street Bets Google Popularity (Blue)')
line1 = base2.mark_line(color="red").encode(y=alt.Y('Close', axis=alt.Axis(title='Daily Closing Price ($)')))
line2 = base2.mark_line().encode(y=alt.Y('wallstreetbets', axis=alt.Axis(title='Google Trend Popularity (0-100)')))

alt.layer(line1, line2).resolve_scale(y = 'independent')
Out[65]:

We see that there is significant correlation between the two datasets. What is interesting, however, is that it appears the decline in search popularity of WallStreetBets spurred the decrease in the GME stock price. The second spike in search popularity could be explained because an influx of people searched the term during the rapid decrease of the GME price.

In [66]:
base = alt.Chart(df_merge).mark_line().encode(
    x=alt.X('Date', axis=alt.Axis(title='Date')), 
    y=alt.Y(alt.repeat('column'), type='quantitative')
    ).properties(title = 'GME Closing Price VS Wall Street Bets Google Popularity', 
    width=600, height=300)

brush = alt.selection(type='interval', encodings=['x'])

background = base.encode(
    color=alt.value('#ddd')
    ).add_selection(brush)

highlight = base.transform_filter(brush)


alt.layer(background, highlight, data=df_merge).repeat(column=["Close", "wallstreetbets"])
Out[66]:

Use Cursor To Highlight range of graph, the highlighted section can be moved to other sections of the graph

Analysis

8. Reflect Pt1



This visualization clearly shows that there is a correlation between the popularity of the search term "wallstreetbets" and the price action of the GME stock. This helps us conclude that the internet, more specifically the r/wallstreetbets reddit community, was a major driving factor in the unprescedented GME short squeeze. To dive deeper, it appears that the decline in the search popularoty of the term actually may have been a factor in the beginning of the decline in the stock price. At the stock's peak, the popularity of the search term hit a local minimum. As the stock price began to fall sharply, people became curius once again hitting another local maximum, followed by a sharp decline.

9. Reflect Pt2



This visualization shows that we can turn messy, large datasets into something easily interpreted by the average human. This is the power of data visualization, especially as we enter the age of big data. As datasets surpass our intellectual capabilities, we must rely on computers and data scientists to reconstruct the data into something with meaning.
